[2] United Nations & WHO

15 Nov 2015 WHO: Ebola then and now
http://www.who.int/features/2015/ebola-then-now-harris/en/
[This is an interesting article by the World Health Organization's Margaret Harris on the difference in the level of Ebola virus disease (EVD) treatment, comparing the treatment in September 2014 to the current level of treatment.]
*******
15 Dec 2015 UN: Special envoy on Ebola speaks with United Nations at press conference
http://bioprepwatch.com/stories/510652919-special-envoy-on-ebola-speaks-with-united-nations-at-press-conference
[Dr. David Nabarro, the United Nations special envoy on Ebola, spoke with the United Nations (UN) News Center in a recent press conference regarding the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak in West Africa. Dr. Nabarro stated the priorities for addressing an outbreak response will be to ensure the EVD survivors are able to obtain needed medical help. He also pointed out the Zaire ebolavirus can live on in certain body fluids after otherwise testing free of EVD, As an example, Dr. Nabarro said these virus remnants can spread through sexual contact, and survivors and health-care providers will need to take special precautions when needed. He also spoke of the need for continued vigilance in the event an EVD flare-up occurs, and said the medical and other services in affected countries will need to be brought back to capacity in order to serve recovery efforts.

The UN also reports the Office of the Special Envoy on Ebola will close at the end of [2015]. Despite this, Dr. Nabarro states the UN presence will still be in place during the remainder of the outbreak. "I will personally stay continuously engaged in the issue, working with the World Health Organization, working with governments, working with partners to try to keep a close eye on what is happening and to ensure that the whole UN system continues to be fully engaged with the affected countries," Nabarro said.]

