[3] Suspected, prevention, post-Ebola syndrome, recovery

15 Dec 2015 Uganda: Health Ministry Rules Out Ebola in Mubende
http://allafrica.com/stories/201512151125.html
[Blood samples drawn from 2 patients admitted to Mubende Regional Referral Hospital with a strange illness last week have tested negative for all contagious heamorrhagic fevers (HF). According to the Director General Health services, Dr Jane Aceng, the blood samples were tested at the Uganda Virus Research Institute and they all tested negative for strains of Ebola, yellow fever and Marburg. "Results returned negative for all hemorrhagic fevers [but see below] and we are still running other tests to establish the cause of the illness," Dr Aceng told Daily Monitor."]
[Not yet ruled out are Lassa fever, Congo-Crimean hemorrhagic fever (CCHF), severe malaria, dengue HF, typhoid. Mubende town is located approximately 172 km (107 mi), by road, west of Kampala, the capital of Uganda. - Mod.JW]
*******
15 Dec 2015 Guinea: Disbelief about Ebola continues 2 years after the beginning of the epidemic
https://internationalmedicalcorps.org/story-guinea-disbelief-around-ebola-as-stubborn-as-the-virus-itself
[Inside (a house), a woman lay in bed with a fever, suffering from abdominal pain, diarrhea, and vomiting -- all possible signs of Ebola. Dr. Ahmed and the team tried to convince the family to let them take her to the nearest Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU) to be tested, but they refused, leaving them with no choice but to turn around and leave the patient in her family's care -- and potentially spread Ebola. They returned the next day and with much difficulty persuaded her to go to the ETU by ambulance. The day after that her test came back negative. But a survey that International Medical Corps conducted in July and August [2015] shows how long it can take to truly change deep-rooted beliefs and behaviors. Of the 190 people interviewed in 5 areas of Guinea, approximately 18 percent (almost 1 in 5) of them still did not believe Ebola was real.]
*******

Prevention
-----
16 Dec 2015: Liberia: Preventive malaria treatment for contacts of patients with Ebola virus disease in the context of the west Africa 2014-15 Ebola virus disease response: an economic analysis
http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(15)00465-X/abstract
[In Liberia during the wet season, malaria preventive treatment was cost saving even when average daily bed-stay costs were as low as USD5 for children younger than 5 years, USD9 for those aged 5-14 years, and USD22 for those aged 15 years or older. Administration of preventive malaria treatment to contacts of patients with Ebola virus disease should be considered by public health officials when addressing Ebola virus disease outbreaks in countries and seasons where malaria reaches high levels of transmission.]
[Prophylaxis eliminates the problem of contacts who develop severe symptoms from malaria being mistaken for suspected EVD cases, and being admitted to an ETU. - Mod.JW]
*******
15 Dec 2015 Uganda:
http://dailynews.co.tz/index.php/home-news/45099-digital-approach-mulled-as-zoonotic-diseases-dog-african-states
["Ebola has never been to East Africa but it is important for us health experts in the region to start taking precautions as such diseases do not choose where to strike," stated Mr Julius Lutwama a medical researcher from Uganda."]
[I`m sure Julius was misquoted; Uganda has had small Ebola outbreaks in 2000-2001, 2007-2008 & 2011-2012 - see ProMED archives, e.g., Ebola virus disease - Uganda (02): (LO) declared Ebola-free Archive Number: 20130117.1502950. I visited Julius at the UVRI on Uganda only last month. He must have been talking about the absence of urban epidemics. - Mod.JW]
*******
15 Dec 2015 USA (CT): Hartford clinic fined, placed on probation for mishandling Ebola-like symptoms
http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-community-health-services-fined-20151214-story.html
[A prominent Hartford [Connecticut] health center has been fined USD 2500 and placed on probation for 1 year for numerous lapses, including mishandling a patient with Ebola-like symptoms. The facility is also required to hire an infection control consultant for at least 3 months who will report to the state Department of Public Health on efforts to correct numerous other violations.]

16 Dec 2015 USA: Protecting the blood supply during a future Ebola outbreak
Although the United States had very few Ebola patients, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) recently released guidance for the collection of blood and blood components. These strategies aim to prevent infection of the [US] blood supply during any future outbreak of the deadly virus. The FDA's new guidance includes the following recommendations for blood banks and related establishments.
Timing: When the CDC has made a determination that none of the countries surveyed have widespread transmission of the Ebola virus, it is appropriate to discontinue screening blood product donors [in the USA] for their risk of having the virus. The following recommendations only apply when the CDC has determined that at least one country has current widespread transmission...]

Post-Ebola syndrome
-----------
16 Dec 2015 USA: New symptoms surface in Ebola patients months after initial recovery
http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-survivor-symptoms-idUKKBN0TZ32B20151216
[Survivors of infection by Ebola virus, already known to face vision, hearing and other problems during their recovery, may also be plagued with health issues such as depression, anxiety and nerve damage that surface after they leave the hospital, according to a small spot survey of 9 victims whose care was managed in the USA. Some of the signs and symptoms can persist for months, researchers from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta found...]

*******

Post-Ebola recovery
------
16 Dec 2015 Sierra Leone: From Ebola response to recovery - the case of President Koroma's post-Ebola recovery and transition program
http://allafrica.com/stories/201512170733.html
[President Koroma's Post-Ebola recovery and transition program is almost 6 months old, and by all indications, there are remarkable improvements in the key priority areas of the delivery plan in all the 14 districts. Under the health sector, for example, majority of the districts have benefited immensely...]

14 Dec 2015 Liberia: Eight-month Ebola program launched
http://allafrica.com/stories/201512142760.html
[On Saturday, 12 Dec 2015, the 2nd component of the Ebola Community Action Platform Project (ECAP-2) was launched in Tubmanville, Neekreen Administrative District of Grand Bassa County.
Funded by the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) and the United States Agency for International Development (OFDA), under the management of Mercy Corps, is being implemented in 1500 communities across Liberia's 15 counties by local non-governmental organizations. The 1st phase of the Ebola Community Action Platform ECAP project was launched in January 2015. The program will build community preparedness by supporting and strengthening local infrastructures and existing health systems to prevent a future outbreak of the Ebola virus or any other disease. According to Shalom Executive Director Mrs. Pate Chon, the project will "basically engage the communities, encouraging them to move into action and take their health matters into their own hands, being able to link with the various clinics."

[Compiled by Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

